snippet.textDisplay:
Digital copies of games are only gonna get worse and worse.
I was one of the dinosaurs that saw the blood on the water as soon as Steam started to become a thing, and alas I was ridiculed for trying to hold on to optical disks.
I see a future where always online will be mandatory and ads will run on the games you bought, yes bought, not just free to play ones.

Remember, cable TV used to be a way for you to buy channels and not see ads. Then sure enough they started running them.
Then stream services came along, again, pay to watch with no ads and again, that's changing.
Even the damn smart TVs you buy will serve you ads now a days, your Xbox too.

I remember speaking against people that would buy games on day 1 then wait for a patch to fix it, it has become the norm, every game needs a patch today.
Up to the early 90's any game that was released with a significant bug had to be recalled, I remember that happening, and financially it was devastating for a company so they generally made dawn sure the thing worked fairly bug free, certainly to a much higher standard than today, RDR2 on PC anyone?
Today they took the online patch safety net to use and abuse, they're completely reliant on it just because people will choose comfort over everything.
They want their games on day one and need to have them right then, but they don't wanna go to a store, digital is so much easier and no sitting in line...
They've open the flood gates not to mention killed a lot of retailers in the process (don't get me started on Amazon) so I hope these great forward looking individuals like the future they created, where they own nothing and make it so there is no competition on retail.
